# OpenMonitor — Cursor AI Rules

## Project Context

C++20 / MFC Win32 Windows desktop application. Build system: MSBuild (Visual Studio 2022, toolset v145).
Displays network speed, CPU/RAM/GPU usage, temperatures in floating window + taskbar widget.

## File Encoding — Critical

- `.rc` resource files: UTF-16 LE — never edit as UTF-8
- `.cpp` / `.h`: UTF-8 without BOM (MSVC interprets as ANSI)
  - NEVER embed literal non-ASCII characters — always use `\uXXXX` C++ escape sequences
  - Example: use `_T("↑")` for ↑, `_T("↓")` for ↓

## Build System

- Always build from `OpenMonitor.sln`, never individual `.vcxproj`
- PlatformToolset: `v145` (must NOT be changed — v143 lacks MFC headers)
- Output: `Bin/x64/Release/OpenMonitor.exe` + DLLs

## Code Patterns

- MFC dialogs derive from `CBaseDialog` → `CDialogEx`
- String resources: `IDS_*` constants, loaded with `CCommon::LoadText()`
- Settings: `CCommonData` struct, persisted as INI via `CSettingsHelper`
- Drawing: Direct2D (`D2D1Support`) for skins, GDI for classic rendering
- No raw `new`/`delete` — use MFC handles and RAII

## MSIX Packaging

- `Package.appxmanifest` controls Store identity
- Startup task `Executable` = `OpenMonitor\OpenMonitor.exe` (DesktopBridge subfolder prefix)
- DLLs go in `OpenMonitor\` subfolder inside the package (set via `<Link>` in .wapproj)

## Plugins

- Implement `IPluginItem` from `include/PluginInterface.h`
- Plugin DLLs placed in `plugins/` folder next to the EXE

## What to Avoid

- Changing PlatformToolset from v145
- Literal non-ASCII in .cpp/.h source files
- Building .vcxproj files directly instead of the .sln
- Putting the signing PFX inside `AppPackages/` (gets cleaned on rebuild)
